%S A395453 1,0,-1,0,-1,2,0,-1,5,-5,0,-1,6,3,-21,14,0,-1,7,7,-28,-28,84,-42,0,-1,
%T A395453 8,8,4,-36,-72,-12,120,180,-330,132,0,-1,9,9,9,-45,-90,-45,-45,165,
%U A395453 495,165,-495,-990,1287,-429
%N A395453 Triangle of the Lagrange inversion coefficients for ordinary formal power series, indexed by partitions in A334439 order.
%C A395453 The terms T(n, lambda) are the coefficients of the compositional inverse g of f, where g(f(x)) = x, for the formal power series f(x) = Sum_{j>=1} a_j * x^j with a_1 = 1. Here, lambda is a partition index, and the partitions lambda |- n follow the sum-length-revlex ordering defined in A334439. The coefficients are given by T(n, lambda) = (-1)^k * (n + k)! / ((n + 1)! * Product_{v} m_v!), where k is the number of parts and m_v is the multiplicity of part v. The empty partition is included, with T(0, []) = 1. For n >= 1, each row begins with a zero column representing the absence of a constant term in the inversion, so T(n, []) = 0.
%C A395453 With these notations, the Lagrange inversion formula in its ordinary form relates the coefficient of the inverse to the sum over partitions of a fixed length k. The contribution of all partitions of n with exactly k parts to the (n+1)-th coefficient of g(x) is:
%C A395453   [x^(n+1)] g(x) (restricted to length k) = Sum_{lambda in P(n, k)} T(n, lambda) Product_{i=1..k} a_{lambda_i + 1} where P(n, k) = {lambda |- n and length(lambda) = k}.
%C A395453 Summing the right-hand side over all partition lengths (k = 1 to n) yields the full coefficient of the inverse series
%C A395453   [x^(n+1)] g(x) = Sum_{lambda |- n} T(n, lambda) Product_{i >= 1} a_{lambda_i + 1}.
%C A395453 For example, choosing a_j = 1 for all j >= 1 gives f(x) = Sum_{j>=1} x^j = x / (1 - x). The compositional inverse is g(x) = x / (1 + x) = Sum_{n>=0} (-1)^n x^(n+1). So Product a_{lambda_i+1} = 1 for every partition, yielding the row sum identity Sum_{lambda |- n} T(n, lambda) = (-1)^n.
%C A395453 The coefficients refine the Schröder triangle A086810. Let S(n, k) = Sum_{j} T(n, j), where the sum collects the partitions of the same length (adjacent terms with equal sign in the table below), then S(n, k) = (-1)^k*A086810(n, k). The triangle A086810 in turn refines the little Schröder numbers A001003, the counts of Schröder trees.
%H A395453 Peter Luschny, <a href="/A395453/b395453.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 0..9320</a>, rows 0..25.
%H A395453 Ira M. Gessel, <a href="https://doi.org/10.48550/arXiv.1609.05988">Lagrange inversion</a>, arXiv:1609.05988 [math.CO], Journal of Combinatorial Theory, Series A, vol 144, 212-249 (2016).
%H A395453 Josef Hofbauer, <a href="https://www.mat.univie.ac.at/~slc/">Lagrange-Inversion</a>, Séminaire Lotharingien de Combinatoire, 6, B06a, (1982).
%H A395453 Joseph Louis Lagrange, <a href="https://gdz.sub.uni-goettingen.de/id/PPN308900308?tify=%7B%22pages%22%3A%5B11%5D%2C%22view%22%3A%22info%22%7D">Nouvelle méthode pour résoudre les équations littérales par le moyen des séries</a>, Mémoires de l'Académie Royale des Sciences et Belles-Lettres de Berlin, vol. 24, pages 251-326; and Oeuvres complète, tome 3, Paris (1867), pp. 5-73.
%H A395453 Peter Luschny, <a href="/A395453/a395453.py.txt">Python implementation</a>.
